{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"FT – Assumptions","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The following assumptions are unique to the FT domain:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1.\tA functional test is not a subjective assessment of how the subject generally performs a task, but rather an objective measurement of the performance of the task by the subject in a specific instance.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT)","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2.\tFunctional tests have documented methods for administration and analysis and require a subject to perform specific activities that are evaluated and recorded. Most often, functional tests are direct quantitative measurements. Examples of functional tests include the Timed 25-Foot Walk, 9-Hole Peg Test, and the Hauser Ambulation Index.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"QRS Shared Assumptions","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The following assumptions are common to the FT and QS domains as well as the Clinical Classifications use case of the RS domain (not the Disease Response use case of RS):","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1.\tThe name of a QRS instrument is described under the variable --CAT in the relevant QRS domain (i.e., FT, QS, RS), and may be either abbreviations or longer names. For example, \"ADAS-COG\", \"BPI SHORT FORM\", and \"APACHE II\" are all --CATs which are shortened names for the instruments they represent, whereas \"4 STAIR ASCEND\" is the FTCAT for the instrument of the same name. Sponsors should always reference CDISC Controlled Terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\tThe QRS Naming Rules for --CAT, --TEST, and --TESTCD and the list of QRS instruments that have published CDISC Controlled Terminology with NCI/EVS are available at: https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b.\tRefer to the following CDISC Controlled Terminology codelists for QRS instrument --CAT terminology:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i.\tCategory of Clinical Classification","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii.\tCategory of Functional Test","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iii.\tCategory of Questionnaire","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"c.\tQRS --TESTCD/--TEST terminology codelists are listed separately by instrument name.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"2.\tNames of subcategories for groups of items/questions are described under the --SCAT variable.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\t--SCAT values are not included in the CDISC Controlled Terminology system but rather controlled as described in the QRS supplements in which they are used.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"3.\tThere are cases where QRS CRFs do not include numeric \"standardized responses\" assigned to text responses (e.g., mild, moderate, severe being 1, 2, 3). It is clearly in everyone's best interest to include the numeric \"standardized responses\" in the SDTMIG QRS dataset. This is only done when the numeric \"standardized responses\" are documented in the QRS CRF instructions, a user manual, a website specific to the QRS instrument, or another reference document that provides a clear explanation and rationale for providing them in the SDTMIG QRS dataset.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"4.\tSponsors should always consult published QRS supplements for guidance on submitting derived information in a SDTMIG QRS domain. Derived variable results in QRS are usually considered captured data. If sponsors operationally derive variable results, then the derived records that are submitted in a QRS domain should be flagged by --DRVFL.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0321_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":321,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\tThe following rules apply for \"total\"-type scores in QRS datasets.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i.\tQRS subtotal, total, etc. scores listed on the CRF are considered captured data and are included in the instrument's controlled terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii.\tQRS subtotal, total, etc. scores not listed on the CRF but documented in an associated instrument manual or reference paper are considered captured data and are included in the instrument's controlled terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"iii.\tQRS subtotal, total, etc. scores not listed on the CRF, but known to be included in eData by sponsors are considered as captured data, are included in the instrument's controlled terminology. The QRS instrument's CT is considered extensible for this case and the subtotal or total score should be requested to be added.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"1.\tAny imputations/calculations done to numeric \"standardized responses\" to produce the total score via transforming numeric \"standardized responses\" in any way would be done as ADaM derivations.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b.\tThe QRS instrument subtotal or total score, which is the sum of the numeric responses for an instrument, is populated in --ORRES, --STRESC, and --STRESN. It is considered a captured subtotal or total score without any knowledge of the sponsor-data management processes related to the score.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i.\tIf operationally derived by the sponsor, it is the sponsor's responsibility to set the --DRVFL flag based on their eCRF process to derive subtotal and total scores. An investigator-derived score written on a CRF will be considered a captured score and not flagged. When subtotal and total scores are derived by the sponsor, the derived flag (--DRVFL) is set to \"Y\". However, when the subtotal and total scores are received from a central provider or vendor, the value would go into --ORRES and --DRVFL would be null (see Section 4.1.8.1, Origin Metadata for Variables).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 4.1.8.1"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"5.\tThe variable --REPNUM variable is populated when there are multiple repeats of the same question. When records are related to the first trial of the question, the variable --REPNUM should be set to \"1\". When records are related to the second trial of the same question, --REPNUM should be set to \"2\", and so forth.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"6.\tThe actual version number of an instrument is represented in the --CAT value as designated by the QRS Terminology Team. If it is determined that this is not the case for an instrument:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\tNotify the QRS Terminology Team that the instrument has a specific or multiple version numbers. This team will assist in providing an resolution on how the situation will be handled.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"b.\tConsider the use of the --GRPID variable to indicate the instrument's version number prior to a decision by the QRS Terminology Team.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"c.\tThe sponsor is expected to provide information about the version used for each QRS instrument in the metadata (using the Comments column in the Define-XML document). This could be provided as value-level metadata for --CAT.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"d.\tThe sponsor is expected to provide information about the scoring rules in the metadata.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"7.\tIf the variable --TEST is represented with verbatim text >40 characters, represent the abbreviated meaningful text in --TEST within 40 characters and describe the full text of the item in the study metadata. If the verbatim item response (e.g., --QSORRES) is >200 characters, represent the abbreviated meaningful text in QSORRES within the 200 characters and describe the full text in the study metadata; see Section 4.5.3, Text Strings that Exceed the Maximum Length for General Observation-class Domain Variables, for further information.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 4.5.3"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\tThe instrument's annotated CRF can also be used as a reference for the full text in both of these situations.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0322_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":322,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"8.\t--EVAL and --EVALID must not be used to model QRS data in SDTM. These variables have had various interpretations on QRS CRFs and were used to represent a multitude of evaluator information about QRS instruments. This has made it more difficult for users of SDTM QRS data to interpret this","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"data and more difficult to pool data for analyses. If needed, supplemental qualifiers may be used to represent this data. Updated information on a proposed solution to this issue will be posted on the CDISC QRS webpage (https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"9.\tAll standard QRS supplement development is coordinated with the CDISC SDS QRS Subteam as the governing body. The process involves drafting the controlled terminology and defining instrument-specific standardized values for qualifier, timing, and result variables to populate the SDTMIG FT, QS, and RS domains. These supplements are developed based on user demand and therapeutic area standards development needs. Sponsors should always consult the CDISC website to review the terminology and supplements prior to modeling any QRS instrument.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"a.\tSponsors may participate and/or request the development of additional QRS supplements and terminology through the CDISC SDS QRS subteam and the Controlled Terminology QRS subteam.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"i.\tOnce generated, the QRS supplement is posted on the CDISC website (https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"ii.\tSponsors should always consult the published QRS supplements for guidance on submitting derived information in SDTMIG-based domains.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0323_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":323,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.1 Functional Tests (FT) — QRS Shared Assumptions","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"10.\tAny identifiers, timing variables, or findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to a QRS domain, but the following qualifiers would generally not be used: --POS, --BODSYS, --ORNRLO, --ORNRHI, --STNRLO, --STNRHI, --STRNC, --NRIND, --XFN, --LOINC, --SPEC, --SPCCND, --LOC, --FAST, --TOX, --TOXGR, --SEV.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:executor","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-28T00:00:00Z"}}
